lderly heckler Statler, groovy girl Janice to freaked-out lab helper Beaker, even early versions of Miss Piggy and Elmo. Hunt also acted, directed and mentored the next generation of performers. His accomplishments are all the more remarkable in that he crammed them all into only 40 years. Richard Hunt was just 18 years old when he joined Jim Henson’s company, where his edgy humor quickly helped launch the Muppets into international stardom. Hunt lived large, savoring life’s delights, amassing a vivid, disparate community of friends. Even when the AIDS epidemic wrought its devastation, claiming the love of Hunt’s life and threatening his own life, he showed an extraordinary sense of resilience, openness and joy. Hunt’s story exemplifies how to follow your passion, foster your talents, adapt to life’s surprises, genuinely connect with everyone from glitzy celebrities to gruff cab drivers – and have a hell of a lot of fun along the way.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aGay menzUnited StatesvBiography. 0aPuppeteerszUnited StatesvBiography. 0aTelevision producers and directorszUnited StatesvBiography. 7aBIOGRAPHY & AUTOBIOGRAPHY / General.2bisacsh  arichard hunt, biography, muppet, fraggle rock, puppet, the muppet show, jim henson, aids, hiv, film, media, pop culture, new jersey, sesame street, puppeteer, children's media.40uhttps://doi.org/10.36019/978197883673040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781978836730423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781978836730/original  aEBA_EMB  aGBV-deGruyter-alles